Problem 1 -- Matching the "stories" to the probability distributions (10 points)

For this problem, you may want to revisit the Probability Distribution Explorer. For each "story" below, state which probability distribution would best describe the scenario and explain why.

A. The time between large (magnitude 8 or higher) earthquakes.

Exponential distribution because it follows that rare events occur with a rate, beta, per unit time.

B. The number of bases DNA polymerase can replicate before making an error.

Geometric distributions because we perform a series of Bernoulli trials with probability of success, theta, until we get a success. The number of failures, y, before the success is geometrically distributed. We did this in the individual portion of HW9 (problem 2).

C. The number of errors DNA polymerase make when replicating the entire genome.

Binomial distribution because with N Bernoulli trials, each trial has a probility of succes (in this case an error).

D. The chance an instrument in the lab will break a given time we go to use it.

Bernoulli distribution because there are only two possible outcomes, the instrument not breaking or breaking.

E. The number of steps Mines students take in a day. Normal distribution because it follows the definitio of being any quantity that emerges as the sum of a large number of subprocesses.

Problem 2 -- The partitioning of carboxysomes (20 points)

Carboxysomes are organelle-like structures that some bacteria have to aid in carbon fixation. Cells generally only have a very few number of carboxysomes (1 to 7), so how they are partitioned to the daughter cells is an interesting question. Researchers specifically looked at cells with 6 carboxysomes, and asked how many went to "daughter cell 1" upon cell division, where the daughter cell of interest was randomly selected. They got the following results:

15% of the time, the daughter cell got 2 carboxysomes 70% of the time, the daughter cell got 3 carboxysomes 15% of the time, the daughter cell got 4 carboxysomes Out of 88 trials, no other number of carboxysomes were ever seen.

A. If the carboxysomes were partitioned randomly, which distribution would best describe the number of carboxysomes seen in daughter cell 1?

B. Simulate this random process of seeing how many carboxysomes go to daughter cell 1. First, simulate with "coin flips" for each of the six carboxysomes in turn, recording how many went to the one cell of interest. Simulate this process 10,000 times, and plot the results. Note that a histogram (with 7 bins) would actually be appropriate here, since there are only a handful of discrete possible results, so there is no concern of binning bias.

import numpy as np

In [2]:
def sim_coinflips(num_reps):
  num_reps_array = np.zeros(num_reps)

  for i in range(num_reps):
    count = 0

    for j in range(6): # repeat for each carboxysome
      carboxy = random.choice(["Y","N"])
      if carboxy == 'Y':
        count += 1
    num_reps_array[i] = count

  return num_reps_array
In [3]:
simm = sim_coinflips(10000)
plt.hist(simm, bins = 7);

D. Given how the results of your simulations compare to the actual experimental results, do you think the partitioning of carboxysomes is random? Why or why not?

The partitioning of carboxysome is not random, we can see from the binomial distribution that when each carboxysome behaves indipendently with a 50% chance of partition, the experimental results are normally distributed and nonrandom.

Problem 3 -- Simulating the Bicoid gradient (20 points)

Bicoid is a key gene in the early development of the fruit fly, Drosophila. The protein is initially only found on the anterior (head) side of the embryo and diffuses further down the embryo over time. This ultimately results in a gradient, with diminishing amounts of Bicoid as you go further along the embryo.

In this problem, we will modify the code for a random walk as shown in class on April 6th to simulate this process of the Bicoid gradient getting set up via a diffusive random walk. For this, we will imagine that all the molecules initially start at position 0, but a key difference will be that molecules cannot take on negative positions. That is, we will treat the left side of the embryo as a boundary that the molecules can not cross. So molecules at position 0 will still have a 50% chance of moving to position 1, but will otherwise stay at position 0.

A. Simulate this modified random walk for 1,000 trajectories (i.e. Bicoid molecules), each with 1,000 steps. Plot the distribution of the final positions of the Bicoid molecules.

n_steps = 1000
n_trajectories = 1000

positions_2D = np.zeros([n_trajectories, n_steps])

for i in range(n_trajectories):

  for j in range(1, n_steps):

    rand = np.random.uniform()

    if rand > 0.5:
      positions_2D[i, j] = positions_2D[i, j-1] + 1

        # step in the negative direction
    else:
      if positions_2D[i, j-1] != 0:
        positions_2D[i, j] = positions_2D[i, j-1] - 1
